docs.abstract: Vanquished and retiring members have been skipping votes, and House Republican leaders are unsure whether they will ever return.
docs.snippet: Vanquished and retiring members have been skipping votes, and House Republican leaders are unsure whether they will ever return.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Just days before a deadline to avert a partial government shutdown, President Trump, Democratic leaders and the Republican-controlled Congress are at a stalemate over the president’s treasured border wall. But House Republican leaders are also confronting a more mundane and awkward problem: Their vanquished and retiring members are sick and tired of Washington and don’t want to show up anymore to vote.

headline.main: A Shutdown Looms. Can the G.O.P. Get Lawmakers to Show Up to Vote?
headline.print_headline: G.O.P. Lame Ducks Fade From House As a Clash Looms

byline.original: By Julie Hirschfeld Davis and Emily Cochrane

docs.abstract: Two reports commissioned by the Senate Intelligence Committee take a deeper look at the fake social media accounts used by Russia in the American election.
docs.snippet: Two reports commissioned by the Senate Intelligence Committee take a deeper look at the fake social media accounts used by Russia in the American election.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Russian influence campaign on social media in the 2016 election made an extraordinary effort to target African-Americans, used an array of tactics to try to suppress turnout among Democratic voters and unleashed a blizzard of activity on Instagram that rivaled or exceeded its posts on Facebook, according to a report produced for the Senate Intelligence Committee.

headline.main: Russian 2016 Influence Operation Targeted African-Americans on Social Media
headline.print_headline: Russian Election Effort  Focused on Influencing African-American Vote

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When lawyers for Texas and 19 other states were deciding where to file a lawsuit seeking to wipe out President Barack Obama’s health care law, they had many choices. But they settled on a federal courthouse in Fort Worth, Tex.

docs.abstract: At the midpoint of his term, the president has grown more sure of his own judgment and more isolated from anyone else’s than at any point since he took office.
docs.snippet: At the midpoint of his term, the president has grown more sure of his own judgment and more isolated from anyone else’s than at any point since he took office.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When President Trump grows frustrated with advisers during meetings, which is not an uncommon occurrence, he sits back in his chair, crosses his arms and scowls. Often he erupts. “Freaking idiots!” he calls his aides. Except he uses a more pungent word than “freaking.”

headline.main: For Trump, ‘a War Every Day,’ Waged Increasingly Alone

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Less than two hours after Defense Secretary Jim Mattis went to the White House on Thursday to hand a resignation letter to President Trump, the president stood in the Oval Office and dictated a glowing tweet announcing that Mr. Mattis was retiring “with distinction” at the end of February.

docs.abstract: Mr. Trump increasingly blames the Fed for the downtrend in stock prices. Some investors say the president himself is the bigger problem.
docs.snippet: Mr. Trump increasingly blames the Fed for the downtrend in stock prices. Some investors say the president himself is the bigger problem.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump has unabashedly hitched his political fortunes to a rising stock market. Now, with stock prices in retreat, he has become increasingly fixated on the idea that one man is to blame for the recent rout: Jerome H. Powell, chairman of the Federal Reserve.

headline.main: Stock Market Rout Has Trump Fixated on Fed Chair Powell
headline.print_headline: Trump Fixates On Fed’s Chief As Stocks Dive

docs.abstract: Former Ohio State University wrestlers — athletes grappling with sexual abuse long buried in their memories — are taking their place in the #MeToo movement.
docs.snippet: Former Ohio State University wrestlers — athletes grappling with sexual abuse long buried in their memories — are taking their place in the #MeToo movement.
docs.lead_paragraph: CLEVELAND — Nick Nutter, an All-American heavyweight wrestler at Ohio State turned professional martial arts fighter, sat watching the television last January as one by one, the young women, former gymnasts — some of them Olympians — took the stand in a courtroom in Michigan, and in wrenching testimony, detailed how their team doctor, Lawrence G. Nassar, had used his power to sexually abuse them.

headline.main: ‘It Can Happen Even to Guys’: Ohio State Wrestlers Detail Abuse, Saying #UsToo

docs.abstract: Lawmakers overwhelmingly approved an $867 billion bill that ditched new work requirements for food stamps that had been embraced by the House and president.
docs.snippet: Lawmakers overwhelmingly approved an $867 billion bill that ditched new work requirements for food stamps that had been embraced by the House and president.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Senate easily passed a sprawling farm bill, 87 to 13, on Tuesday, advancing an ambitious $867 billion measure that rejected stricter work requirements for food-stamp recipients that were pushed by House Republicans and cheered by President Trump.

headline.main: Senate, Rejecting Curbs on Food Stamps, Passes Compromise Farm Bill
headline.print_headline: Senate Passes Farm Bill, Minus Food Stamp Curbs
